However it will take a lot to lift the mood of the fans. Some supporters inside the Estadio Mineirao burned a Brazilian flag and many left after 29 minutes on Tuesday night, when the hosts were 5-0 down.

Those who remained booed their team off at half-time and then cheered and clapped the Germans in the second half as a sign of their disapproval towards the Selecao.

Manager Luiz Felipe Scolari has called on his players to restore some pride to the nation by ending the World Cup with a victory.

Brazil's hopes of winning the World Cup on home soil were dashed in the most brutal fashion on Tuesday when Germany ran out 7-1 winners.

A wave of anger towards Scolari and his players followed the humiliation, but the Brazil coach rejected calls for him to resign.

The defiant 65-year-old held up a sheet of paper during a press conference that followed the defeat, detailing his record of just three losses in 28 matches.

